title: Ramda: Tighten type signature for `append`
body:
[The Ramda documentation clearly states](http://ramdajs.com/docs/#append) that the element to append an the elements in the list should have the same type.
The previous type definition unnecessarily weakened type safety. For example this error could not be detected by TypeScript:

```typescript
interface A {
    id: number
}
const list: A[] = []
R.append({idd: 2}, list)
```

Which seems ridiculous. If one wanted an intersection type, one could explicity define it to be used for the list/element type. Additionally, the function `prepend` already is as strict as this proposal, that should probably be consistent.

I also deleted a redundant line.

title: [big.js] named module export
body:
Big.js now has a named export, so it can be nicely imported with the es6 module syntax. This rewrites the typings to make use of that. Also fixes the interfaces so that the instance interface is properly separated from the constructor interface, and the types can also be imported (no need to rely on the global namespaced types).

~This now only includes the module typings, so the typings for the global variable version are removed. Is this a problem? I expect it not to be, since node uses the commonjs version, and browser code is practically always bundled and uses the same commonjs code~
